digraph RetroQuestReturns {
	graph [
		goal="Build RetroQuest Returns: a modern retrospective board web app using Go (stdlib), htmx + Tailwind CSS, and PostgreSQL. Tier 1 features: team create/login, 3 default thought columns (Happy, Confused, Sad), thoughts CRUD with unlimited voting, action items CRUD with completion and assignee, end retro/archive, SSE real-time updates, responsive layout."
	]
	rankdir=LR

	start [shape=Mdiamond, label="Start"]
	exit  [shape=Msquare, label="Exit"]

	analyze [
		shape=box,
		label="Analyze Old Codebase",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=25,
		prompt="You are analyzing a deprecated web application called RetroQuest to produce a feature specification for its replacement. The old codebase is at deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/ in your working directory.

All Java source files are under deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/api/src/main/java/com/ford/labs/retroquest/ (abbreviated as SRC/ below).

=== PROCESS ===

Work in 4 batches. After each batch, IMMEDIATELY write your findings to ANALYSIS_NOTES.md (create it on batch 1, append on subsequent batches). Do NOT move to the next batch until your notes are written. Once notes are written for a batch, do NOT re-read those source files -- your notes are your reference.

BATCH 1 - Team domain (read these files, then write notes):
- SRC/team/Team.java
- SRC/team/TeamService.java
- SRC/team/TeamController.java
- SRC/team/CreateTeamRequest.java
- SRC/team/LoginRequest.java
Note: fields, authentication flow, password hashing, team name validation rules.

BATCH 2 - Thought and ActionItem domains (read these files, then append notes):
- SRC/thought/Thought.java
- SRC/thought/ThoughtService.java
- SRC/thought/ThoughtController.java
- SRC/thought/CreateThoughtRequest.java
- SRC/actionitem/ActionItem.java
- SRC/actionitem/ActionItemService.java
- SRC/actionitem/ActionItemController.java
- SRC/actionitem/CreateActionItemRequest.java
Note: entity fields, CRUD operations, voting mechanics, discussed flag, assignee handling.

BATCH 3 - Column, Board, and real-time (read these files, then append notes):
- SRC/column/Column.java
- SRC/column/ColumnService.java
- SRC/column/ColumnController.java
- SRC/board/Board.java
- SRC/board/BoardService.java
- SRC/board/BoardController.java
- SRC/board/Retro.java
- SRC/websocket/WebsocketService.java
- SRC/websocket/events/WebsocketEventType.java
Note: default columns, board lifecycle (create/end retro/archive), websocket event types and routing.

BATCH 4 - Database schema and frontend overview (then append notes):
- deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/api/src/main/resources/db/changelog.xml
- Run: find deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/ui/src/App -type f -name '*.tsx' | head -40
Note: table definitions, column types, frontend page structure.

=== AFTER ALL BATCHES ===

Read your ANALYSIS_NOTES.md, then write FEATURE_SPEC.md defining the Tier 1 feature set for the new application:

- Team management: create team (name + password), login with team name + password, no individual user accounts
- Retro board: 3 default thought columns (Happy, Confused, Sad) created when a team is created. Action Items is a separate section, not a thought column.
- Thoughts: create, edit, delete thoughts in Happy, Confused, and Sad columns. Unlimited voting (increment a counter, no per-user tracking). Mark as discussed.
- Action items: create, edit, delete. Fields: task text, assignee (free text), completed (boolean). Displayed in a separate Action Items section alongside the thought columns.
- End retro / archive: archive the current board (thoughts become read-only historical records), action items carry forward unless completed
- Real-time: all connected clients see changes immediately via Server-Sent Events (SSE)
- Responsive layout: works on desktop and mobile

For each feature, document: what it does, the user interaction flow, and any important business rules from the old code. Keep it concise and actionable -- this document will be the input to the design stage.

Tech stack for the new version (do NOT implement yet, just note in the spec):
- Backend: Go, standard library only (net/http), no frameworks
- Frontend: HTML templates rendered server-side, htmx for dynamic interactions, Tailwind CSS for styling
- Database: PostgreSQL via pgx driver
- Real-time: SSE + Postgres LISTEN/NOTIFY
- Architecture: monolith (single Go binary)"
	]

	design [
		shape=box,
		label="Design Architecture",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=25,
		check_cmd="go build ./...",
		prompt="You are designing the architecture for RetroQuest Returns. Read FEATURE_SPEC.md for the complete feature specification.

Your job is to produce TWO things:
A) A DESIGN.md prose blueprint
B) Go contract files that define the exact interfaces and types all implementation stages must use

The Go contract files are the source of truth. Every downstream stage will implement these interfaces and use these exact types. The compiler will enforce consistency.

=== PART A: DESIGN.md ===

Write a file called DESIGN.md covering:

1. PROJECT STRUCTURE: the Go project layout (cmd/server/, internal/server/, internal/models/, internal/db/, internal/handlers/, internal/sse/, internal/auth/, internal/tmpl/, templates/, static/, migrations/)

2. DATABASE SCHEMA: every table with columns, types, constraints, indexes. Tables: teams (TEXT PK from slug), columns (UUID PK), boards (UUID PK), thoughts (UUID PK), action_items (UUID PK). Use ON DELETE CASCADE. Board_id on thoughts is nullable (NULL=active, non-null=archived).

3. HTTP API ROUTES: every route with method, path, handler, description. Use Go 1.22+ ServeMux patterns. Include: login, create team, logout, board view, thought CRUD+heart+discuss, action item CRUD+complete+assignee, column title update, end retro, archives, SSE events.

4. TEMPLATE STRUCTURE: all HTML templates and what they render (base.html, login.html, create.html, board.html, column.html, thought_card.html, action_items.html, action_item_card.html, archives.html, archived_board.html).

5. SSE EVENT DESIGN: per-column events (column-{id}-update), action item events, end-retro page reload. Postgres LISTEN/NOTIFY on 'retro_events' channel.

6. AUTHENTICATION: HMAC-SHA256 signed cookies, bcrypt passwords, RequireAuth middleware.

=== PART B: Go Contract Files ===

Create these Go files. They MUST compile together (go build ./... must pass). Use panic(\"not implemented\") for function bodies.

1. go.mod -- module github.com/campallison/retroquest-returns, Go 1.22+, require github.com/jackc/pgx/v5 and golang.org/x/crypto

2. internal/models/models.go -- ALL domain struct types with exact field names, Go types, and json tags:
   - Team: ID (string), Name (string), Password (string, json:\"-\"), FailedAttempts (int), DateCreated (time.Time), LastLoginDate (*time.Time)
   - Column: ID (string), TeamID (string), Topic (string), Title (string)
   - Board: ID (string), TeamID (string), DateCreated (time.Time)
   - Thought: ID (string), TeamID (string), ColumnID (string), BoardID (*string), Message (string), Hearts (int), Discussed (bool), DateCreated (time.Time)
   - ActionItem: ID (string), TeamID (string), Task (string), Assignee (*string), Completed (bool), Archived (bool), DateCreated (time.Time)

3. internal/db/repository.go -- a Repository interface with EVERY query method:
   type Repository interface {
       CreateTeam(ctx context.Context, team models.Team) (models.Team, error)
       GetTeamByID(ctx context.Context, id string) (models.Team, error)
       GetTeamByName(ctx context.Context, name string) (models.Team, error)
       UpdateLastLogin(ctx context.Context, teamID string) error
       CreateDefaultColumns(ctx context.Context, teamID string) ([]models.Column, error)
       GetColumnsByTeam(ctx context.Context, teamID string) ([]models.Column, error)
       GetColumnByID(ctx context.Context, id string) (models.Column, error)
       UpdateColumnTitle(ctx context.Context, id, title string) error
       CreateBoard(ctx context.Context, teamID string) (models.Board, error)
       GetArchivedBoards(ctx context.Context, teamID string) ([]models.Board, error)
       CreateThought(ctx context.Context, thought models.Thought) (models.Thought, error)
       GetActiveThoughtsByColumn(ctx context.Context, columnID string) ([]models.Thought, error)
       GetThoughtsByBoard(ctx context.Context, boardID string) ([]models.Thought, error)
       UpdateThoughtMessage(ctx context.Context, id, message string) error
       DeleteThought(ctx context.Context, id string) error
       IncrementHearts(ctx context.Context, id string) (int, error)
       ToggleDiscussed(ctx context.Context, id string) (bool, error)
       CreateActionItem(ctx context.Context, item models.ActionItem) (models.ActionItem, error)
       GetActiveActionItems(ctx context.Context, teamID string) ([]models.ActionItem, error)
       UpdateActionItem(ctx context.Context, id, task string) error
       UpdateAssignee(ctx context.Context, id string, assignee *string) error
       DeleteActionItem(ctx context.Context, id string) error
       ToggleCompleted(ctx context.Context, id string) (bool, error)
       EndRetro(ctx context.Context, teamID string) (models.Board, error)
       Notify(ctx context.Context, channel, payload string) error
   }

4. internal/auth/auth.go -- exported function and type signatures with panic stubs:
   - func HashPassword(password string) (string, error)
   - func CheckPassword(password, hash string) bool
   - func SetSessionCookie(w http.ResponseWriter, teamID string)
   - func ClearSessionCookie(w http.ResponseWriter)
   - func GetTeamIDFromRequest(r *http.Request) (string, error)
   - func RequireAuth(next http.Handler) http.Handler
   - func ValidateTeamName(name string) error
   - func ValidatePassword(password string) error
   - func TeamNameToSlug(name string) string

5. internal/sse/hub.go -- Hub struct with method signatures (panic stubs):
   - type Event struct { Type string; Data string }
   - type Hub struct { ... fields for client tracking with sync.RWMutex ... }
   - func NewHub() *Hub
   - func (h *Hub) Subscribe(teamID string) (<-chan Event, func())  // returns channel and unsubscribe func
   - func (h *Hub) Broadcast(teamID string, event Event)
   - func (h *Hub) ServeHTTP(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request, teamID string)

6. internal/tmpl/renderer.go -- Renderer interface:
   - type Renderer interface {
         Render(w io.Writer, page string, data any) error
         RenderFragment(w io.Writer, fragment string, data any) error
         RenderFragmentToString(fragment string, data any) (string, error)
     }

After creating all files, run 'go mod tidy' via the shell tool to resolve dependencies. Then run 'go build ./...' to verify everything compiles.

CRITICAL: The contract files MUST compile. If go build fails, fix the errors before finishing. These files are the foundation that all subsequent stages depend on."
	]

	scaffold [
		shape=box,
		label="Scaffold Project",
		model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=20,
		check_cmd="go build ./...",
		prompt="You are setting up the project skeleton for RetroQuest Returns. Read DESIGN.md for the architecture.

IMPORTANT: The design stage has already created contract files: go.mod, internal/models/models.go, internal/db/repository.go, internal/auth/auth.go, internal/sse/hub.go, and internal/tmpl/renderer.go. Read all of them first. Do NOT overwrite or modify these files. Your job is to create the REMAINING skeleton around them.

Create these files and directories:

1. cmd/server/main.go -- main entry point stub that imports the packages and has a minimal main() that compiles
2. internal/server/server.go -- NewServer function stub that takes a db.Repository, *sse.Hub, and tmpl.Renderer
3. internal/db/db.go -- database connection helper (pgx pool)
4. internal/db/migrate.go -- migration runner (reads .sql files from migrations/ in sorted order, executes each in a transaction)
5. internal/handlers/ -- create handler files with stub functions for each route group:
   - team.go, thought.go, action_item.go, board.go, sse.go
   - Each handler struct should hold a db.Repository, *sse.Hub, and tmpl.Renderer
   - All handler methods should be stubs that return http.StatusNotImplemented
6. templates/base.html -- base layout with Tailwind CSS CDN and htmx CDN in head, basic nav
7. static/.gitkeep
8. migrations/001_create_tables.sql -- full schema DDL from DESIGN.md
9. docker-compose.yml -- Postgres service (postgres:16, port 5432, retroquest db)
10. .env.example with DATABASE_URL and PORT

After creating all files, run 'go mod tidy' then 'go build ./...' to verify everything compiles.

SCOPE: Do NOT implement business logic. Do NOT modify the contract files from the design stage. All handler methods should be stubs. The purpose is a compiling skeleton."
	]

	db_layer [
		shape=box,
		label="Implement DB Layer",
		model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=25,
		check_cmd="go test ./internal/db/...",
		prompt="You are implementing the database layer for RetroQuest Returns using test-driven development.

IMPORTANT: The design stage created contract files that define the exact interfaces you must implement. Read these FIRST:
- internal/db/repository.go (the Repository interface -- you MUST implement every method)
- internal/models/models.go (domain types -- do NOT modify)
- DESIGN.md (for schema and architecture)

Then read the scaffold code:
- internal/db/db.go
- internal/db/migrate.go
- migrations/001_create_tables.sql

=== TDD PROCESS ===

Follow a test-driven development cycle for each Repository method:

1. WRITE THE TEST FIRST in internal/db/postgres_test.go. Since the Docker sandbox does not have a running PostgreSQL, guard all DB tests with:
   func TestMain(m *testing.M) {
       if os.Getenv(\"DATABASE_URL\") == \"\" {
           fmt.Println(\"skipping DB tests: DATABASE_URL not set\")
           os.Exit(0)
       }
       os.Exit(m.Run())
   }
   This ensures 'go test ./internal/db/...' passes in the sandbox (skipped = success).

2. Write the test for a method (e.g., TestCreateTeam), using table-driven tests and github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp for assertions. Run 'go get github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp' first.

3. Implement the method in internal/db/postgres.go to satisfy the test.

4. Run 'go test ./internal/db/...' to confirm it compiles and the test is skipped (no DATABASE_URL).

5. Move to the next method. Repeat the cycle.

=== IMPLEMENTATION ===

1. internal/db/db.go -- Connection pool setup using pgx/v5/pgxpool with Connect and Ping.

2. internal/db/migrate.go -- Read .sql files from migrations/ directory in sorted order, execute each in a transaction.

3. internal/db/postgres.go (new file) -- A struct that implements the Repository interface:
   - type PgRepository struct { pool *pgxpool.Pool }
   - func NewPgRepository(pool *pgxpool.Pool) *PgRepository
   - Implement EVERY method from the Repository interface using parameterized SQL queries
   - EndRetro should be transactional (Begin/Commit/Rollback)
   - CreateDefaultColumns should create Happy, Confused, Sad columns with matching topics

CRITICAL: Do NOT modify internal/db/repository.go or internal/models/models.go. Your PgRepository MUST satisfy the Repository interface exactly.

SCOPE: Do NOT write HTTP handlers or templates. Only implement the data layer and its tests."
	]

	backend [
		shape=box,
		label="Implement Backend Logic",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=35,
		check_cmd="go test ./internal/auth/... ./internal/handlers/... ./internal/sse/...",
		prompt="You are implementing the authentication, HTTP handlers, and SSE hub for RetroQuest Returns using test-driven development.

IMPORTANT: Read the contract files FIRST -- they define the exact function signatures and interfaces you must implement:
- internal/auth/auth.go (function signatures with panic stubs -- replace the panics with real implementations)
- internal/sse/hub.go (Hub struct and methods with panic stubs -- replace with real implementations)
- internal/db/repository.go (Repository interface -- handlers receive this interface, NOT a concrete DB type)
- internal/models/models.go (domain types -- do NOT modify)
- internal/tmpl/renderer.go (Renderer interface -- handlers call Renderer.Render and Renderer.RenderFragment)
- DESIGN.md

Then read the existing code:
- internal/db/postgres.go (implements Repository)
- internal/handlers/ (stub files)

=== TDD PROCESS ===

Follow a strict test-driven development cycle for EVERY function you implement:

1. WRITE THE TEST FIRST. For each function or handler method, write a failing test before writing any implementation code.

2. For handler tests, create a mockRepository struct in your _test.go files that implements db.Repository with configurable return values. For auth tests, test signing/verification, cookie round-trips, middleware behavior, and validation functions. For SSE tests, test subscribe/unsubscribe, broadcast routing, and slow client handling.

3. Run 'go test' and CONFIRM the test fails (compilation error, panic from stub, or wrong behavior). This proves the test is actually testing something.

4. Write the MINIMUM implementation to make the test pass.

5. Run 'go test' again and confirm GREEN. Only then move to the next function.

TESTING CONVENTIONS:
- Use table-driven tests with t.Run(tc.name, ...)
- Use github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp for ALL assertions
- Place test files next to the code: internal/auth/auth_test.go, internal/handlers/team_test.go, etc.

=== WHAT TO IMPLEMENT ===

1. AUTHENTICATION (internal/auth/auth.go) -- replace panic stubs:
   - HashPassword/CheckPassword using bcrypt
   - SetSessionCookie/ClearSessionCookie/GetTeamIDFromRequest using HMAC-SHA256 signed cookies
   - RequireAuth middleware that checks cookie and sets team_id in request context
   - ValidateTeamName, ValidatePassword, TeamNameToSlug
   - Use COOKIE_SECRET from environment with a dev fallback

2. HANDLERS (internal/handlers/) -- each handler struct holds a db.Repository, *sse.Hub, and tmpl.Renderer:
   team.go: HandleLoginPage, HandleLoginSubmit, HandleCreatePage, HandleCreateSubmit, HandleLogout
   thought.go: HandleCreateThought, HandleUpdateThought, HandleDeleteThought, HandleUpvoteThought, HandleDiscussThought, HandleColumnFragment, broadcastColumnUpdate helper
   action_item.go: HandleCreateActionItem, HandleUpdateActionItem, HandleDeleteActionItem, HandleCompleteActionItem, HandleAssignActionItem, HandleActionItemsFragment
   board.go: HandleRetroBoard, HandleEndRetro, HandleUpdateColumn, HandleArchivesPage, HandleArchivedBoard
   sse.go: HandleEvents (delegates to hub.ServeHTTP)

3. SSE HUB (internal/sse/hub.go) -- replace panic stubs:
   - NewHub, Subscribe (returns channel + unsubscribe func), Broadcast (non-blocking), ServeHTTP

CRITICAL: Do NOT modify internal/models/models.go, internal/db/repository.go, or internal/tmpl/renderer.go.

SCOPE: Do NOT write HTML templates."
	]

	frontend [
		shape=box,
		label="Implement Frontend",
		model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=25,
		prompt="You are implementing the frontend templates for RetroQuest Returns. Read the contract files and handler code to understand the exact data structures templates receive.

Start by reading:
- internal/models/models.go (exact struct field names your templates must use)
- internal/tmpl/renderer.go (Renderer interface -- understand page vs fragment rendering)
- internal/handlers/ (all files -- see what template data each handler passes)
- DESIGN.md (template structure section)
- templates/base.html (existing scaffold)

Then implement ALL templates with htmx and Tailwind CSS:

1. templates/base.html -- Complete the base layout:
   - Include Tailwind CSS via CDN (https://cdn.tailwindcss.com)
   - Include htmx via CDN (https://unpkg.com/htmx.org@2.0.4)
   - Include htmx SSE extension (https://unpkg.com/htmx-ext-sse@2.3.0/sse.js)
   - Responsive nav bar with app name, team name (when logged in), logout link
   - Content block for page-specific content
   - Use a clean, modern color scheme (e.g., indigo/slate brand colors)

2. templates/login.html -- Login page:
   - Form with team name and password inputs, submit button
   - POST to /login, display inline error on failure
   - Link to create team page
   - Centered card layout, mobile-friendly

3. templates/create.html -- Create team page:
   - Form: team name, password, confirm password
   - POST to /create, display inline error on failure
   - Link back to login

4. templates/board.html -- Main retro board (the core page):
   - Connect to SSE endpoint using hx-ext='sse' and sse-connect='/team/{teamId}/events'
   - 4-section responsive grid: Happy, Confused, Sad thought columns + Action Items section
   - Each column uses sse-swap='column-{id}-update' for live updates
   - Action items section uses sse-swap='action-item-update'
   - End Retro button with confirmation dialog
   - Mobile bottom navigation for switching between columns
   - Include JavaScript for inline editing of thoughts and action items

5. templates/column.html -- Partial: column with header, create input, thought cards
   - Color-coded header by topic (emerald for happy, sky for confused, rose for sad)
   - Inline-editable column title via htmx
   - Thought creation form with hx-post and hx-swap='none' (SSE handles the update)
   - Thought count display
   - Scrollable thought list

6. templates/thought_card.html -- Partial: single thought card
   - Message text with discussed styling (strikethrough, dimmed)
   - Heart/upvote button with count
   - Discuss toggle button
   - Edit button (launches inline edit via JavaScript)
   - Delete button with hx-confirm

7. templates/action_items.html -- Partial: action items section
   - Violet-colored header
   - Action item creation form
   - Item count display
   - Scrollable list of action item cards

8. templates/action_item_card.html -- Partial: single action item card
   - Complete checkbox toggle
   - Task text (editable inline)
   - Assignee field
   - Delete button with hx-confirm
   - Completed items visually dimmed

9. templates/archives.html -- Archives page with tabs for thought archives and action item archives
10. templates/archived_board.html -- Single archived board view (read-only)

Use the Go template 'dict' helper function for passing multiple values to partials (e.g., {{template \"thought_card\" (dict \"Thought\" . \"TeamID\" $.TeamID)}}).

Make all templates responsive using Tailwind breakpoints. The retro board should feel pleasant and modern.

SCOPE: Do NOT modify Go source files. Only create or edit files in the templates/ directory."
	]

	wiring [
		shape=box,
		label="Wire Server",
		model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=25,
		check_cmd="go test ./...",
		prompt="You are wiring together all components of RetroQuest Returns into a working server, using test-driven development for the template renderer.

IMPORTANT: Read the contract files FIRST:
- internal/tmpl/renderer.go (the Renderer interface you MUST implement)
- internal/db/repository.go (Repository interface -- NewServer accepts this, not a concrete pool)
- internal/models/models.go (domain types)
- internal/auth/auth.go (RequireAuth middleware)
- internal/sse/hub.go (Hub)
- internal/handlers/ (handler structs -- see what dependencies they need)
- internal/server/server.go (current state)
- cmd/server/main.go (current state)
- DESIGN.md

=== TDD PROCESS for TemplateRenderer ===

1. Write tests FIRST in internal/tmpl/tmpl_test.go:
   - Test Render with a simple test template
   - Test RenderFragment with a partial
   - Test RenderFragmentToString returns correct HTML string
   - Test error cases (unknown template name)
   Use table-driven tests and go-cmp.

2. Run 'go test ./internal/tmpl/...' to confirm tests fail (panic from unimplemented interface or compile error).

3. Implement TemplateRenderer to make the tests pass.

4. Run 'go test ./...' to confirm ALL tests pass (including tests from previous stages).

=== WHAT TO IMPLEMENT ===

1. internal/tmpl/tmpl.go -- A struct that implements the Renderer interface:
   - type TemplateRenderer struct { pages, fragments map[string]*template.Template }
   - func NewTemplateRenderer(dir string) (*TemplateRenderer, error) -- loads and parses all templates
   - Implement Render, RenderFragment, RenderFragmentToString from the Renderer interface
   - FuncMap with helpers: 'dict', 'deref' (*string), 'formatDate'

2. internal/server/server.go -- Server setup:
   - NewServer(repo db.Repository, hub *sse.Hub, renderer tmpl.Renderer) *http.ServeMux
   - Wire each handler struct with repo, hub, and renderer
   - Register all routes using Go 1.22+ method-based patterns
   - Apply auth.RequireAuth middleware to /team/* routes
   - Serve static files from static/

3. cmd/server/main.go -- Entry point:
   - Load .env file
   - Connect to PostgreSQL, create db.NewPgRepository(pool)
   - Run migrations, parse templates via tmpl.NewTemplateRenderer
   - Create sse.NewHub(), wire into server.NewServer
   - Start Postgres LISTEN/NOTIFY listener goroutine
   - Start HTTP server

CRITICAL: Do NOT modify contract files (repository.go, renderer.go, models.go, auth.go signatures, hub.go signatures). Your TemplateRenderer MUST satisfy the tmpl.Renderer interface.

SCOPE: Do NOT modify handler logic or database queries. Only wire and implement the template engine."
	]

	integration_tests [
		shape=box,
		label="Integration Tests",
		model="anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		max_rounds=25,
		check_cmd="go test ./...",
		prompt="You are writing integration and end-to-end tests for RetroQuest Returns.

The implementation stages have already written unit tests as part of their TDD process. Your job is to write INTEGRATION tests that the unit tests cannot cover -- tests that exercise complete request/response cycles through the full HTTP stack.

Start by reading:
- ALL existing test files (*_test.go) to understand what is already covered
- internal/server/server.go (route wiring)
- internal/handlers/ (all handler implementations)
- internal/auth/auth.go (middleware)
- internal/db/repository.go (Repository interface)

=== WHAT TO WRITE ===

Create internal/server/integration_test.go (or split across files as needed):

1. MOCK SETUP: Create a comprehensive mockRepository that implements db.Repository with configurable behavior (stored data in maps, configurable errors). Also create a mock Renderer if needed.

2. TEST HELPER: Create a setupTestServer() helper that wires a real http.ServeMux with mock dependencies and returns an httptest.Server.

3. INTEGRATION TESTS using httptest.NewServer:
   - Login flow: GET /login -> POST /login with valid credentials -> verify redirect + cookie set
   - Create team flow: POST /create -> verify team created, columns created, cookie set, redirect
   - Unauthorized access: GET /team/myteam/board without cookie -> verify redirect to login
   - Thought lifecycle: create thought -> verify SSE event broadcast -> update thought -> delete thought
   - Action item lifecycle: create -> toggle complete -> update assignee -> delete
   - End retro: POST end-retro -> verify board created, SSE event sent
   - Column update: PUT column title -> verify SSE broadcast

4. SSE INTEGRATION: Test that SSE endpoint streams events correctly when thoughts/action items are modified.

TESTING CONVENTIONS:
- Use table-driven tests with t.Run(tc.name, ...)
- Use github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp for ALL assertions
- Each test should be independent -- create fresh mock state per test

After writing tests, run 'go test ./...' and ensure ALL tests pass (both the new integration tests and all existing unit tests from previous stages). If a test reveals a genuine application bug, document it in TEST_NOTES.md but do NOT fix the application code.

SCOPE: Do NOT fix application bugs -- document them in TEST_NOTES.md."
	]

	review_fix [
		shape=box,
		label="Review and Fix",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=2,
		max_rounds=20,
		check_cmd="go test ./...",
		prompt="You are reviewing the entire RetroQuest Returns codebase for correctness and completeness. Read every Go source file, every template, every test file, the migration SQL, and the design documents.

Perform these checks systematically:

1. COMPILATION AND TESTS: Run 'go test ./...' via the shell tool. ALL tests must pass. If any fail:
   - Determine whether the failure is a bug in the application code or a bug in the test
   - Fix whichever is wrong
   - Re-run until all tests pass
   Also read TEST_NOTES.md if it exists -- the testing stages may have documented application bugs they found but did not fix. Fix those bugs now.

2. ROUTE CONSISTENCY: Compare internal/server/server.go routes with internal/handlers/ implementations. Every registered route must have a corresponding handler. Every handler must be wired.

3. TEMPLATE CORRECTNESS: Check that:
   - Every template referenced in handlers exists in templates/
   - Template data fields match what handlers pass
   - htmx attributes (hx-post, hx-get, hx-delete, hx-put, hx-target, hx-swap) reference correct URLs
   - SSE event names in templates match what the backend sends

4. DATABASE: Check that:
   - All queries use parameterized inputs (no SQL injection)
   - Migration SQL matches the models in internal/models/
   - Foreign key references are correct

5. FEATURE COMPLETENESS: Compare against FEATURE_SPEC.md and DESIGN.md:
   - Is every Tier 1 feature implemented?
   - Are there any missing handlers or templates?

6. SECURITY: Check for:
   - Password hashing (bcrypt) on team creation
   - Auth middleware on all /team/* routes
   - No secrets hardcoded in source

7. TEST COVERAGE: Review the test suite:
   - Are there unit tests for auth, handlers, SSE, and template rendering?
   - Are there integration tests for complete request flows?
   - If any areas lack tests, add them following TDD conventions (table-driven, go-cmp).

Fix every issue you find. After fixing, run 'go test ./...' again to confirm all tests still pass.

Write a file called REVIEW_NOTES.md documenting what you found and fixed."
	]

	final_check [
		shape=box,
		label="Final Verification",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=2,
		max_rounds=15,
		goal_gate=true,
		retry_target="review_fix",
		check_cmd="go test ./...",
		prompt="You are performing the final verification of RetroQuest Returns. A previous review stage already found and fixed issues. Read REVIEW_NOTES.md to see what was addressed.

Do a focused check on these areas:

1. Run 'go test ./...' via the shell tool. ALL tests must pass. If any fail, fix the issue and re-run until green. This is non-negotiable -- the pipeline cannot exit with failing tests.

2. Read cmd/server/main.go and internal/server/server.go -- verify the server starts correctly, all routes are registered, middleware is applied.

3. Read every handler file in internal/handlers/ -- verify each handler:
   - Reads request data correctly
   - Calls the right database function
   - Returns the right template partial or redirect
   - Sends NOTIFY for real-time updates where appropriate

4. Read every template in templates/ -- verify:
   - base.html includes all CDN links (Tailwind, htmx, htmx-sse)
   - board.html has correct SSE connection setup
   - All partials have correct htmx attributes
   - Responsive classes are present

5. Read internal/sse/hub.go -- verify SSE implementation:
   - Clients can connect and disconnect cleanly
   - Events are broadcast to correct team
   - Postgres LISTEN is set up

6. Check that go.mod lists all required dependencies (pgx, bcrypt, go-cmp).

7. Verify test quality: spot-check a few test files. Are they using table-driven patterns? Are they using go-cmp? Do they have meaningful assertions?

Fix any remaining issues you find. This is the last stage before the pipeline completes, so be thorough.

Update REVIEW_NOTES.md with any additional findings from this pass."
	]

	start -> analyze -> design -> scaffold -> db_layer -> backend -> frontend -> wiring -> integration_tests -> review_fix -> final_check -> exit
}
